Equities in South Africa Rise for a Second Day, Led by Anglo, BHP Billiton

-- B y   L a u r e n   v a n   d e r   W e s t h u i z e n   a n d   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 
2011-04-20T15:43:14Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-20/equities-in-south-africa-rise-for-a-second-day-led-by-anglo-bhp-billiton.html
The FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index
climbed for a second day, rising 689.24, or 2.2 percent, to
32,526.30 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following are among the most active stocks in the South
African market today.  Allied Technologies Ltd. (ALT)  , a maker of television
set-top boxes, rose for the second day, gaining 2.39 rand, or
4.3 percent, to 57.60 rand. Full-year revenue increased to 9.7
billion rand ($1.4 billion) from 9.2 billion a year earlier, the
company said in a regulatory filing.  Anglo American Plc (AAL)  , the diversified mining company
that makes up 11 percent of  South Africa ’s benchmark stock
index, advanced 9.30 rand, or 2.7 percent, to 352 rand, a second
day of increases. Copper rallied for a second day and platinum
rose for the first day in three on signs the global economy is
recovering.  BHP Billiton  Plc (BIL SJ), the world’s largest
mining company, added 5.48 rand, or 2 percent, to 281.73 rand,
taking its gain this year to 6.1 percent.  Impala Platinum
Holdings Ltd. (IMP)  , the second-biggest producer of the
metal, climbed 8.95 rand, or 4.8 percent, to 194.95 rand.  Pick n Pay Stores Ltd. (PIK)  , South Africa’s second-
largest grocer, snapped two days of losses, rising 1.20 rand, or
3 percent, to 41.75 rand. An arbitrator resolved that it had the
right to terminate a labor flexibility and mobility agreement
with the South African Commercial, Catering and Allied Workers’
Union, the company said in a regulatory filing today.  Pretoria Portland Cement Co. Ltd. (PPC SJ), a South African
maker of the building material, dropped the most since Jan. 31,
losing 99 cents, or 3.9 percent, to 24.50 rand. The cement maker
said earnings per share may be as much as 40 percent lower in
the six months through March from a year earlier.  Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, rose the most since April 5, adding 8.29 rand,
or 2.3 percent, to 374.78 rand. Oil advanced for a second day in
 New York , climbing as much as 2.6 percent, as signs of an
improving economy in the U.S., the world’s biggest consumer of
crude, stoked speculation demand for fuel may increase.  Vodacom Group (VOD SJ), the largest provider of mobile-
phone services to  South Africans , climbed 2 rand, or 2.7
percent, to 77.50 rand, the biggest increase since March 30. The
company’s recommendation was raised to “buy” at Deutsche Bank
AG.  To contact the reporters on this story:
